attributes.title: choicemt1: Tracking the dynamics of deliberate judgment
Nudging Eyewitnesses: The Effect of Social Influence on Recalling Witnessed Events

q1.value: Nudging Eyewitnesses: The Effect of Social Influence on Recalling Witnessed Events

q2.value: Kirk Luther, Brent Snook, Zak Keeping, Weyam Fahmy

q3.value:
Conducting effective and efficient witness interviews requires substantial effort and cooperation from witnesses. One of the main forms of cooperation that interviewers seek is the provision of detailed and accurate information. The objective of this project is to examine the effect of adding a nudging technique to a well-established memory aid on interviewee recall. Specifically, does the addition of Social Proof to the Report All mnemonic within the Cognitive Interview improve an interviewee’s recall?

We conducted a lab-based experiment examining the effect of different social influence strategies (i.e., consistency, reciprocity, authority, social proof) on the quality and quantity of information provided by eyewitnesses (see  https://osf.io/uwqmb/; henceforth Experiment 1). Participants (N = 174) watched a video depicting vandalism in a convenience store and were asked to recall the witnessed event. Participants were assigned randomly to one of six conditions, which included Control (participants given an open-ended prompt), Engage and Explain (participants told of the ground rules for the interview), Consistency (participants signed an agreement to work hard), Reciprocity (participants given water and food), Authority (participants told of interviewer’s training), and Social Proof (participants shown transcript from an exemplar participant). We found that participants in the Social Proof condition spoke for a longer period of time and recalled more correct details than participants in all other conditions. 

To follow-up on the results of Experiment 1, the purpose of Experiment 2 is to determine whether the effects of Social Proof on recall performance would be replicated, and to examine the incremental effect of Social Proof on the Report All Cognitive Interview mnemonic. Experiment 2 will be hosted on the online platform Prolific (survey built on Qualtrics). Participants will be recruited through the platform’s participant pool and will be assigned randomly to one of four conditions, which will include a Control, Social Proof, Report All (instruction encouraging interviewees to report everything without editing), or Social Proof + Report All. The participants will watch a video of the vandalism incident (as in Experiment 1), will be administered the manipulation that corresponds with the condition they were assigned to, and then asked to recall the witnessed event by typing their response in a textbox.

q4.value: We hypothesize a main effect of Social Proof, whereby participants exposed to this manipulation will: (a) have longer written responses (i.e., greater number of words), (b) recall more correct details, (c) recall fewer incorrect details, and (d) provide slightly more confabulations, than those in the Control condition. We also hypothesize a main effect of the Report All manipulation, whereby participants exposed to this manipulation will also: (a) have longer written responses (i.e., greater number of words), (b) recall more correct details, (c) recall fewer incorrect details, and (d) provide slightly more confabulations than those in the Control condition. Finally, we hypothesize an interaction, whereby Social Proof will increase the benefits of the Report All manipulation on recall performance (i.e., increase the number of correct details, reduce the number of incorrect details, and increase confabulations slightly). No hypothesis are formed as to the relative difference between the Social Proof and Report All conditions in terms of recall performance (exploratory).

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they have been assigned.

question.value: A 2 (Social Proof: Present, Absent) x 2 (Report All Mnemonic: Present, Absent) between-participants design will be used. The independent variable is the interview procedure with four levels: (1) Control, an open-ended prompt; (2) Social Proof, (3) Report All, the Cognitive Interview mnemonic that encourages interviewees to report all information they can remember; and (4) Social Proof + Report All. The dependent variables are: response length (number of words), correct details recalled, incorrect details recalled, confabulations, and error rate.

q9.value: Participants will be randomly assigned to one of the four conditions listed above. Given that we are using an online survey platform, we will use the random assignment function on Qualtrics to conduct such randomization.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: We will recruit and collect data via the online survey platform, Prolific Academic. The population from which we are drawing our sample is the population of Prolific Academic users. Participants who fail to answer the questions in the audio-visual test correctly (indicating that they could not hear or see the video) will be excluded will be excluded from the analyses. Additionally, participants who fail to follow the study instructions (i.e.., fail to respond to the questions appropriately; e.g., participant provides an account of an event that is unrelated to the video they viewed). The study will be posted online until we reach our desired sample of 200 participants.

q13.value: The target sample size is 200 participants.

q14.value: A a priori power analysis was conducted with G*Power 3.1 (MANOVA: Special Effects and Interactions; f = .25, α = .05, power = .95, number of groups = 4, response variables: 5 [talking time, number correct details, incorrect details, confabulated details, error rate]) and revealed that a sample size of 200 (i.e., 50 participants in each condition) is required.

q15.value: We have full control over the sample size.

question.value:
The following are text instructions/intended manipulations provided to participants in each condition:

Control (i.e., open-ended prompt):
Please tell me in as much detail as possible everything you can remember about the events you witnessed on video a few moments ago.

Social Proof Manipulation:
Before you begin your recall of the video you just watched, you should be aware of what recall in an interviewing context normally looks like – this will give you an idea of what you should try to achieve when recalling what you saw in the video. 
Most participants take their time and think about everything carefully so they are able to recall almost all of the details from the video without making any mistakes. 
On the next page, there is a picture of the recall from an ideal participant. The statement is blurred for privacy purposes, but you can see that this participant recalled a lot of information, and the information provided was accurate.
 
[see attached image below; this image will be presented to the participant for 5 seconds. The screen will automatically advance to the next page when the 5 seconds have elapsed]

I hope that telling you about this ideal participant will help you understand what I’m hoping you can achieve with your participation in this study. Please type your response in the box below.

[Participant Responds]

[Participants Advances to the Next Screen]

What else do you remember?
[Participant Responds]

Report All Manipulation:
I would like for you to tell me everything you can remember, even the things that you think are not important, and even if you can’t remember something completely. 

Don’t worry if it seems out of order or place. Everything you have to tell me here today is important. All of your information is valuable.

Please tell me in as much detail as possible everything you can remember about the events you witnessed on video a few moments ago. Please type your response in the box below.

Social Proof + Report All:
Before you begin your recall of the video you just watched, you should be aware of what recall in this setting normally looks like – this will give you an idea of what you should try to achieve with your recall.
 
Most participants take their time and think about everything carefully so they are able to recall almost all of the details from the video without making any mistakes. 
On the next page, there is a picture of the recall from an ideal participant. The statement is blurred for privacy purposes, but you can see that this participant recalled a lot of information, and the information provided was accurate. 
I hope that telling you about this ideal participant will help you understand what I’m hoping you can achieve with your participation in this study.
 
[see attached image below; this image will be presented to the participant for 5 seconds. The screen will automatically advance to the next page when the 5 seconds have elapsed]


I would like for you to tell me everything you can remember, even the things that you think are not important, and even if you can’t remember something completely. 

Don’t worry if it seems out of order or place. Everything you have to tell me here today is important. All of your information is valuable.

Please tell me in as much detail as possible everything you can remember about the events you witnessed on video a few moments ago. Please type your response in the box below.

We will be measuring five variables: 
Response length: participants’ response length to the open-ended prompt will be measured by counting the number of words the participants typed into the text box using the word count feature of Microsoft Word.

Participants’ responses will be used to create three coding guides – one for correct details, one for incorrect details, and one for confabulations. Every participant’s response will be coded for discrete correct, incorrect, and confabulated details according to the coding guides.

Correct Details: The total number of correct details will be computed for each participant.

Incorrect Details: The total number of incorrect details will be computed for each participant.

Confabulated Details:  The total number of confabulated details will be computed for each participant.

Error Rate: [(incorrect details + confabulated details) / (correct details + incorrect details + confabulated details) ]*100.

A mean will be computed for each of the dependent variables (i.e., response length, and correct, incorrect, and confabulated details recalled) for each condition. These means will be used in the analyses to determine whether there any significant differences in participants’ recall performance across the four experimental conditions.

A 2 (Social Proof: Present, Absent) x 2 (Report All Mnemonic: Present, Absent) Multivariate Analysis of Variance (MANOVA) will be conducted. Bayesian analyses will also be conducted to determine the extent to which the data support the null and alternative hypotheses.

q20.value: Participants’ responses will be used to create three coding guides – one for correct details, one for incorrect details, and one for confabulations. Every participant’s response will be coded for discrete correct, incorrect, and confabulated details. Given that the participants’ witnessed a video clip, their accounts will be limited to audio and visual details. Any detail that is mentioned at least once will be added to the coding guide.

q21.value:
p-value: less than .05
Bayes factors: Following the interpretation guidelines provided by Wagenmakers et al. (2018)

q22.value: A boxplot analysis will be used to determine extreme outliers (National Institute of Standards and Technology, 2006; Tabachnick & Fidell, 2013). The extreme outliers will be removed from the main analysis; an analysis including the extreme outliers will be presented in the Appendix.

q23.value: Incomplete or missing data will be excluded from analysis.

q24.value: An exploratory test will be conducted to compare the relative difference between the Social Proof and Report All conditions in terms of recall performance.
